Advice: Unless you really know what you're getting into, don't use either of
Xenia to Columbus is mostly farmland with little shade.
Cincinnati to Xenia is mostly wooded and shady. (deciduous)
Zipcar: 3 locations in OTR and Downtown and 1 at UC.
Greyhound: Daily trips to most american cities. Park surreptitiously in the casino garage. There is a large, covered rack on the
Amtrak: 3 trains each week, in the middle of the night. Chicago to New York. There is one outdoor rack out front, but you should consider parking elsewhere.
There is no transit to Union Terminal.
Megabus: Daily trips to regional cities. Stops at UC and various downtown locations.
'Metro Plus' is a limited line. Stops are indicated .

Frequent Transit: all buses have bike racks on the front with room for two bikes. Sometimes they are full, but usually not. Uphill segments of frequent lines are shown here. On average, you should expect to wait about 7 minutes (between 0 and 15 minutes) for these lines daytime on weekdays. Sundays and times after the evening rush hour have less frequent service.
Other Transit: Many lines are not shown, though most spots on this map are within walking distance of transit running all day.
#11 comes closest to the Little Miami trailhead. Catch it here.

A network of asphalt-paved trails connects Cincinnati to most of Ohio. Most towns have a place to eat, get water and use the toilet. Repair shops are somewhat less common and one might do worse than to carry a spare tube.
Trails generally follow old rail lines and are very flat as a result.

Airport: Park in the Fountain Square garage downtown and take the TANK 2X to the airport. The (express) bus runs about hourly and costs $2.00. The Fountain Square garage has an underground, covered, and very well monitored bike rack.
Bikeshare: Coming summer 2014 to Downtown and OTR.
Mobo is a bicycle coop. The Bike Kitchen is basically a coop for UC students. Both offer free tools, help with repairs and some trivial parts.
All other shops ( ) on this map are regular retail stores selling parts and tools and making repairs.
There are public repair stands ( ) at Xavier, UC and Rookwood Commons, near the Student Union, Bike Kitchen and Whole Foods respectively.
Line thickness indicates the width of streets.
Line color indicates posted speed limits.
